article.headline: Season-high turnovers doom Magic
article.linkText: Bucks outlast Magic for third straight win
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Michael Redd and the short-handed Milwaukee Bucks were determined to extend their winning streak. Redd scored 29 points and the Bucks got 15 points and a career-high 14 rebounds from center Dan Gadzuric in a 111-105 win over the Orlando Magic on Wednesday night. The Bucks, who had only 11 players in uniform because of injuries, got contributions from 10 of them in recording their third straight victory. Desmond Mason added 21 points and Zaza Pachulia, starting for the first time this season, had nine points and 11 rebounds. With the win, Milwaukee matched its best run of the season. "We're tired of losing," said Redd, who shot 12-for-19. "We look at the standings and we're last in our division and that's no fun. We knew we had a tough stretch coming up had had to get some wins and we did that." Steve Francis nearly had a triple-double for Orlando with 24 points, 12 rebounds and nine assists. Grant Hill had 26 points and Cuttino Mobley added 17 for the Magic, who were undone by 23 turnovers. "We're not playing well and it begins on the defensive end, but it extends to the offensive end and taking care of the basketball," Magic coach Johnny Davis said. "A lot of those turnovers were unforced errors. We're throwing the ball around carelessly like we've never played together." Milwaukee scored 31 points of Orlando turnovers and shot 49 percent in the win. Whenever Orlando missed, Gadzuric and Pachulia were there for putbacks. The Bucks' big men had nine of the team's 12 offensive rebounds. "We realized what we should have realized before, which is that everybody has to hold up their responsibility," Gadzuric said. "We came out real strong and everybody held up their roles the rest of the game." The Magic trailed the entire game, but used a 9-1 run at the start the fourth quarter to pull within 87-86 on a driving layup by Hedo Turkoglu with 9:30 left. Mike James hit a 3-pointer for Milwaukee to stop the run and Orlando never got closer than four the rest of the game. "What we need is better execution, better decision making and a commitment to just be flat-out tough," Davis said. The Magic committed a season-high 14 turnovers in the first half, which the Bucks turned into 19 points on their way to a 56-50 halftime lead. Milwaukee shot 56 percent in the half and all 10 players in uniform had at least one field goal. Mobley kept Orlando close with 13 points on 5-for-5 shooting from the field in the first half, including three 3-pointers. The Bucks scored seven straight late in the third period to take an 11-point advantage, their biggest of the game. Two free throws by Mason gave Milwaukee an 84-73 lead with 1:13 left in the third quarter.

Game notes
Bucks F Keith Van Horn was placed on the injured list with tendinitis in his right ankle. That makes five Bucks currently on the injured list. ... Milwaukee F Joe Smith sat out the game with a groin strain. He is listed as day-to-day. ... The Magic are second in the NBA in scoring at 101.8 a game, but last in points allowed per game at 101.1. They have yielded an average of 111.8 points in their last six losses. ... Pachulia started two games as a rookie in Orlando last season. ... Mobley is third in the NBA in 3-point field goal percentage at 49 percent. Mobley was 3-of-5 on 3-pointers against the Bucks.
